ternal URLs, they'd either be relative paths starting with `/` or have no netloc at all. I'll add the main entry point and ensure the app runs properly. it's external by checking if it has a network location component. If `parsed.netloc` exists, it's an absolute URL pointing to an external domain, so I reject it. Otherwise, I allow the redirect with a 302 status code. I also need to handle the naming conflict—Flask's `redirect` function and my route function can't share the same name, so I'll keep the route as `redirect_route` and import `redirect` directly from Flask. allow relative paths like `/home`, `/path/to/page`, and `relative/url` while blocking absolute URLs with domains such as `http://example.com`, `https://example.com/path`, and protocol-relative URLs like `//example.com`. The `netloc` check handles all these cases correctly—relative paths have an empty `netloc` and get redirected, while any URL with a domain gets rejected.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":28761,"output_tokens":1957,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":10,"output_tokens":1957,"cache_read_input_tokens":28761,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":{"applied_edits":[]}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"66682cee-d0ae-4f25-989a-27b297e0a9bb","uuid":"6adfc298-4797-4532-84c7-000000000000","request_id":"req_011CbdMRFYjgr7tpfe8eD3ex"}
